\chapter*{Preface}

In December 2022 a friend of mine mentioned that a company called Jane Street posts a ``puzzle'' each month. They aren't typical puzzles, though (like a jig-saw or crossword), they are usually, rather, a fairly complicated math- and/or computer-science-oriented brain teaser. Here's the statement of that month's puzzle, \emph{Die Agony}:
\[
\input{die-agony-grid}
\]
\begin{quote}
A six-sided die, with numbers written on each of its faces, is placed on the 6-by-6 grid above, in the lower-left (yellow) corner. It then makes a sequence of ``moves''. Each move consists of tipping the die into an orthogonally adjacent square within the grid.

The die starts with a ``score'' of 0. On the $N$th move, its score increases by $N$ times the value of the die facing up after the move. However, the die is only allowed to move into a square if its score after the move matches the value in the square. Also, the die cannot be translated or rotated in place in addition to these moves.

After some number of moves the die arrives in the upper-right (blue) corner.

The answer to this puzzle is the sum of values in the unvisited squares from the die's journey.
\end{quote}

Being the nerd I am, I was immediately hooked and worked on it nonstop until I found the solution. And if you find it interesting, too, I suggest you stop reading this right now and either try it or Jane Street's current puzzle yourself.

Needless to say, I had a lot of fun for a number of reasons, though it was especially satisfying to get to apply a bit of group theory I learned that semester. I realized I could represent the result of tipping the die in different directions on the arrangement of numbers on the die faces with members from $S_6$, the group of permutations with six elements. For example, if the top, east, north, west, south, and bottom faces of the die (from a bird's-eye view perspective) are respectively labelled 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6, tipping the die to the right corresponds to the permutation $(1264)$ in \emph{cycle notation}.\footnote{I.e., 1 goes to 2, 2 goes to 6, 6 goes to 4, 4 goes to 1, and 3 and 5 don't change. See \url{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation#Cycle_notation} for more.}












