I spent a weekend thinking about and eventually solving that month's puzzle called \emph{Die Agony}, and I had a lot of fun. So every now and then I worked on a puzzle to tackled August 2024's \emph{Tree-edge Triage}, which was  and had so much fun solving it that I wanted   it so much that I wrote an explanation of it in \LaTeX. Though after I was finished, I realized a more rewarding (and ambitious) project would be to explain the problem and its solution for a general audience---not just those roughly familiar with undergraduate math and computer science. Not only this, but That is a tall order, though, for sure, some of Jane Street's .\footnote{Example (August 2023's Single-Cross 2): Consider 3-space (i.e.\ $\mathbf{R}^3$) partitioned into a grid of unit cubes with faces defined by the planes of all points with at least one integer coordinate. For a fixed positive real number $D$, a random line segment of length $D$ (chosen uniformly in location and orientation) is placed in this cubic lattice.

What length $D$ maximizes the probability that the endpoints of the segment lie in orthogonally adjacent unit cubes (that is, the segment crosses exactly one integer-coordinate plane), and what is this maximal probability? Give your answer as a \textbf{comma-separated pair of values to 10 significant places} (e.g.\ ``1.234567891,0.2468135792'').}

The hope is that Chapter \ref{prelim} will offer enough of an introduction to the basic but powerful (mathematical) ideas that are needed for solving these tricky but also really cool puzzles. 
